Strict Language Requirements:

Mandatory Language: You must communicate, explain, and respond exclusively in Hebrew.

No Exceptions: Under no circumstances should you provide explanations, comments, or chat responses in English or any language other than Hebrew, unless you are specifically asked to provide a code snippet (where the code syntax remains in its original language).

Consistency: Even if the user asks you in English, your response must remain exclusively in Hebrew.

Reasoning and Chain of Thought: All internal reasoning steps (if displayed) and final output must be in Hebrew.

Agent Communication Protocol:

Thoughts and Outlines: All internal reasoning, step-by-step plans, and task outlines must be written in Hebrew.

Action Descriptions: When describing an action you are about to perform (e.g., "I will now check..."), use Hebrew only.

Error handling: Even when reporting a failure (such as "failed to import"), explain the error and your next steps in Hebrew.

In addition, I don't understand programming at all, so there are no exceptions: Under no circumstances should you provide explanations, comments, or chat responses in a programming language or any language that is not understandable to a person who has no programming background, but rather adapt the explanations to understandable and simple language, as if you were explaining to your client that he is not currently interested in programming, but only in the finished product.

I want you to handle the Git sync. Every time you finish a task, push it to GitHub automatically.

UI/UX & Layout Guidelines for Complex Multi-Column Layouts
Project Structure & Styling Rules:

Multi-Layered Layout: The layout must support a hierarchical structure with at least three distinct content areas on a single page:

Main Header/Primary Content: Positioned at the top, spans the full width or a significant portion.

Secondary Content (Level 1): Two-column layout immediately below the primary section.

Tertiary Content (Level 2): High-density, multi-column layout (at least 2 columns) at the bottom section.

Typography Hierarchy:

Primary Text: Larger font size, increased line-height, bold headers.

Secondary Text: Medium density, clear separation from primary text using horizontal dividers or padding.

Tertiary Text: Smallest font size, maximum information density, using justified alignment to maintain a "classic" book-like appearance.

Visual Separators: Use clean, subtle borders or spacing to define the boundaries between the different text blocks (Main, Side-notes, and Footnotes).

Responsive Alignment: Ensure that when text flows between columns, the vertical rhythm is maintained across the page.

Text Justification: All text blocks should be perfectly justified (left and right) to create a structured, professional "grid" look.

Container Logic: Each section (Main, Sub-section 1, Sub-section 2) should be encapsulated in its own semantic container to allow independent scrolling or formatting if necessary.